  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses {(growthRatePhase1 * 100)}% growth and {(discountRate * 100)}% discount rate. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100).toFixed(1)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & Limitations</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what this DCF inherently misses.</p>

  <h3>Downside Risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Pressures:</strong> Ongoing scrutiny of Pharmacy Benefit Managers (PBMs) could threaten Evernorth's margins, a significant driver of cash flow.</li>
    <li><strong>Medicare Advantage:</strong> Changes to reimbursement rates or utilization spikes in the Medicare Advantage population can pressure the health benefits segment.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> Cigna carries a substantial amount of debt resulting from historical acquisitions. High interest rates make refinancing more expensive, which could eat into FCF.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Upside Potential</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Evernorth Expansion:</strong> Continued growth in specialty pharmacy and care services through Evernorth could provide higher-margin revenue streams.</li>
    <li><strong>Share Buybacks:</strong> Consistent capital return programs mean fewer shares outstanding over time, driving up per-share value.</li>
  </ul>

